Nonbreeding adult.description: Adult Lesser Black-backed Gulls are smaller than Great Black-backed Gulls with a paler gray back and wings. They also have yellowish legs, whereas Great Black-backed Gulls have pink legs.

Juvenile.description: Juvenile Lesser Black-backed Gulls can be separated from juvenile Great Black-backed Gulls by the smudges around their eye. They also have an entirely black bill unlike juvenile Great Black-backed Gulls that have pink at the base of the bill.

Breeding adult (American).description: Adult Herring Gulls have much paler upperparts than Great Black-backed Gulls.

Nonbreeding adult.description: Nonbreeding adult Herring Gulls can be separated from Great Black-backed gulls by their smaller size and paler gray upperparts.

Second winter (American).description: Second winter Herring Gulls are more heavily streaked on the neck, head, and breast than second or first winter Great Black-backed Gulls.

Breeding adult.description: Adult Western Gulls look similar to Great Black-backed Gulls, but they are smaller and a paler shade of gray. Their ranges also do not usually overlap.

Adult.description: Adult Great Black-backed Gulls are so large and dark that they can be confused with adult Bald Eagles when flying at a great distance. The eagles show all-dark bodies as well as wings that are more uniformly broad than a gull.
